I have found that the close review functionality will not work unless I am listed as a reviewer.
{code:java}
{
  "code": "NotPermitted",
  "message": "You do not have permission to Close the review CR-BSL-24"
}{code}
Seems logical. So I try to use the reviewers API to add myself with the comma delimited user list in the body. I authenticate via the API, but I get a 403 forbidden when I try this.
{code:java}
{
  "code": "NotPermitted",
  "message": "Anonymous user cannot add reviewers to a review."
}{code}
If I use Basic Authentication
{code:java}
{
  "code": "NotPermitted",
  "message": "You do not have permission to join this review."
}{code}
I can go into Crucible and "Join the review to add myself via the UI, and then I can add others, and close the ticket using the API.

I discussed this with the team who manages our Atlassian products and they said there are no restrictions on the reviews that prevent someone from adding themselves. Is there an additional check in the API, that I must adhere to?

 

thanks

Mark

Each project page: http://\{site}/project/\{project}

Has a link to http://\{site}/changelog/\{project}/\{path}

Clicking on this link results in, "The requested resource cannot be found.

Path "\{path}" does not exist."

 

Maybe the link should not be shown if clicking on it would generate a 404.

*Steps to reproduce*
 * Create a revision and upload a patch. Most probably any diff will do, but the following one is proven to exhibit the problem:
{noformat}
diff --git a/PasswordResetMailTest.java b/PasswordResetMailTest.java
index 96764ab..35da422 100644
--- a/PasswordResetMailTest.java
+++ b/PasswordResetMailTest.java
@@ -91,6 +91,7 @@ public class PasswordResetMailTest extends MailEnabledTestBase {
         assertNotSubstring("<body>", content);
     }
 
+    //test
     public void testHtmlVerificationEmailContent() throws Exception {
         String content = subtestVerificationEmailContent(MailMessage.CONTENT_TYPE_HTML);
         assertSubstring("<html>", content);

{noformat}

 * Open Add Content > Pre-commit window and expand a path in Existing Patches section

 

*Expected behavior*
 Affected files are listed with numbers of lines added and deleted

 

*Actual behavior*
 !screenshot-1.png!

h2. Actual behaviour

Currently when any perforce related error happens when FishEye tries to get [p4 filelog|https://www.perforce.com/perforce/r16.1/manuals/cmdref/p4_filelog.html] for a batch of file revisions, it tries to fall back recursively. It splits the batch and tries to get information for smaller batches. 

Code which splits list is broken and leads to throwing away last element of that list.

File: {{com.cenqua.fisheye.perforce.client.P4Client#execFilelog}}
{code:java}int size = fileList.size(); 
if (size > 1) { 
   int midPoint = size / 2; 
   execFilelog(changeLists, fileList.subList(0, midPoint), importMode); 
   execFilelog(changeLists, fileList.subList(midPoint, size - 1), importMode);
}{code}
 
h2. Impact

Because of this bug some file revisions will have incorrect metadata being associated with them, e.g. Java Text file will can be marked as _binary_ revision.

 
h2. Expected behaviour 

FishEye correctly handles which come from Perforce, correctly fallbacks from batch mode and does not loose any file revision information. In case of persistent errors, propagate the exception into upper callee levels.
